04748nam a22006615i 9781846158414DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20112011xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97818461584147 a10.1515/97818461584142doi  a(DE-B1597)674272  a(OCoLC)796383932  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 4aBX2470 7aREL0330002bisacsh04a271.009022221 aKatherine Smith, Katherine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWar and the Making of Medieval Monastic Culture /cKatherine Katherine Smith. 1aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (250 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in the History of Medieval Religion ;v3700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1 Encountering War in the Scriptures and Liturgy -- t2 Monks and Warriors: Negotiating Boundaries -- t3 Spiritual Warfare: The History of an Idea to c.1200 -- t4 Martial Imagery in Monastic Texts -- t5 Warriors as Spiritual Exemplars -- tConclusion -- tAppendix: The Loricati, c.1050–1250 -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe monastic life, traditionally considered as an area of withdrawal from the world, is here shown to be shaped by metaphors of war, and to be actively engaged with battle in the world outside.An extremely interesting and important book. makes an important contribution to the history of medieval monastic spirituality in a formative period, whilst also fitting into wider debates on the origins, development and impactof ideas on crusading and holy war. Dr William Purkis, University of Birmingham Monastic culture has generally been seen as set apart from the medieval battlefield, as "those who prayed" were set apart from "those whofought". However, in this first study of the place of war within medieval monastic culture, the author shows the limitations of this division. Through a wide reading of Latin sermons, letters, and hagiography, she identifies a monastic language of war that presented the monk as the archetypal "soldier of Christ" and his life of prayer as a continuous combat with the devil: indeed, monks' claims to supremacy on the spiritual battlefield grew even louder asChurch leaders extended the title of "soldier of Christ" to lay knights and crusaders. So, while medieval monasteries have traditionally been portrayed as peaceful sanctuaries in a violent world, here the author demonstrates thatmonastic identity was negotiated through real and imaginary encounters with war, and that the concept of spiritual warfare informed virtually every aspect of life in the cloister. It thus breaks new ground in the history of European attitudes toward warfare and warriors in the age of the papal reform movement and the early crusades. Katherine Allen Smith is Assistant Professor of History, University of Puget Sound.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMonasticism and religious orders -- History -- Middle Ages, 600-1500. 0aMonasticism and religious ordersxHistoryyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 0aWar and society -- Europe -- History -- To 1500. 0aWar and societyzEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval History. 4aMilitary History. 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh  aEarly Crusades.  aMetaphors of War.  aMonastic Life.  aPapal Reform Movement.  aSoldier of Christ.  aSpiritual Battlefield.  aWar.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184615841440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846158414423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846158414/original